<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-460-038  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 460 038.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 24 1989 v6 n29 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Old ARPANETs never die; they just migrate to DRI. (AdvancedResearch Projects Agency Network) (Defense Research Internet)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ubois, Jeff.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Department of Defense is changing the roles of its two mostimportant networks, ARPANET and the Defense Data Network (DDN).andO;Much of what used to be ARPANET is now DDN and ARPANET will beretired between 1989 and 1994.andP;  DDN will be used to serve theday-to-day secure communications needs of the military.andP;  ARPANETwill be replaced by DRI, which will be used primarily forexperimental and research purposes.andP;  DRI will support the DefenseAdvanced Research Projects AGency's research in the areas ofcommand, control and communications and will become a part of theNational Research Network.andP;  DRI and DDN must both confrontchallenges that include making way for increased growth,implementing standards, maintaining security and making sure thatDDN is integrated into a single network.andP;  Many of the newtechnologies that are now under development for these militarynetworks will eventually migrate into the commercial market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryARPANETSecurityUpgradingNetworksUnited States. Department of DefenseDefense Data Network (Computer network)Defense Research Internet (computer network).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>